#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:21
msgid "Agree on and define common error handling terminology"
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:23
msgid ""
"Recoverable error: An error that can be reacted and recovered from when "
"encountered e.g. a missing file."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:24
msgid ""
"Unrecoverable error: An error that cannot reasonably be reacted to or "
"recovered from and which indicates a bug e.g. indexing out of bounds."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:25
msgid ""
"Error Type: A type that represents a recoverable error. Error types can "
"optionally implement the `Error` trait so that it can be reported to the "
"user or be converted into a trait object."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:26
msgid ""
"Reporting Type: A type that can store all recoverable errors an application "
"may need to propagate and print them as error reports."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:27
msgid ""
"Reporting types can represent the recoverable errors either via concrete "
"types, likely parameterized, or trait objects."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:28
msgid ""
"Reporting types often bundle context with errors when they are constructed, "
"e.g. `Backtrace`."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:29
msgid ""
"Reporting types often provide helper functions for creating ad hoc errors "
"whose only purpose is to be reported e.g. `anyhow::format_err!` or `eyre::"
"WrapErr`."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:31
msgid "Come to a consensus on current best practices"
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:33
msgid "Here is a tentative starting point, subject to change:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:35
msgid "Use `Result` and `Error` types for recoverable errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:36
msgid "Use `panic` for unrecoverable errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:37
msgid ""
"Implement `Error` for error types that may need to be reported to a human or "
"be composed with other errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:38
msgid ""
"Use enums for types representing multiple failure cases that may need to be "
"handled."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:39
msgid ""
"For libraries, oftentimes you want to support both reporting and handling so "
"you implement `Error` on a possibly non-exhaustive enum."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:40
msgid ""
"Error kind pattern for associating context with every enum variant without "
"including the member in every enum variant."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:41
msgid ""
"Convert to a reporting type when the error is no longer expected to be "
"handled beyond reporting e.g. `anyhow::Error` or `eyre::Report` or when "
"trait object + downcast error handling is preferable."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:42
msgid ""
"Recommend `Box`ing concrete error types when stack size is an issue rather "
"than `Box`ing and converting to `dyn Error`s."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:43
msgid ""
"What is the consensus on handling `dyn Error`s? Should it be encouraged or "
"discouraged? Should we look into making `Box<dyn Error...>` implement "
"`Error`?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:46
msgid "Identify pain points in error handling today"
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:48
msgid ""
"Backtrace capture is expensive, but without one it can be difficult to "
"pinpoint the origin of errors"
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:49
msgid ""
"unwrap on errors without first converting to a reporting type will often "
"discard relevant information"
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:50
msgid ""
"errors printing from main have to assume a prefixed `Error: `, sub par "
"control of output format when printing during termination."
msgstr ""

#: src/2965-project-error-handling.md:51
msgid ""
"Error trait only exposes 3 forms of context, can only represent singly "
"linked lists for chains of errors"
msgstr ""

